Adaptive query execution, or A-Q-E.

Before Spark three point zero, Catalyst made every decision upfront, using estimated statistics. The trouble is that estimates are often wrong. Adaptive query execution fixes this by re-optimizing the plan at runtime — after each shuffle — using the real partition statistics it just measured.

There are three things A-Q-E actually does.

First, it dynamically coalesces partitions. If a shuffle produces two hundred partitions, but most of them are tiny, A-Q-E merges them into a smaller number of right-sized partitions. That cuts down on task-startup overhead.

Second, it switches the join strategy at runtime. A sort-merge join can be promoted to a broadcast join, if one side turns out to be small enough once it has actually been measured.

Third, it handles skew. It splits oversized partitions, so that one slow task does not stall an entire stage. We cover skew in detail in the performance-tuning module.

Here is the mental model to keep. This is the same Catalyst optimizer, but now it gets a second chance at each stage boundary, working with facts instead of guesses. And A-Q-E has been on by default since Spark three point two.
